apsular collection of oral contrast material in the liver seen on CT. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em>2003; 181: 598–599.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=AJR+Am+J+Roentgenol&amp;publication_year=2003&amp;pages=598">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">30.</div><div id="R30" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Meyers</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">MA</span></span>. The extraperitoneal space: normal and pathologic anatomy. In: Meyers MA, ed. Dynamic radiology of the abdomen. 5th ed. New York, NY: Springer-Verlag, 2000; 333–492.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=MeyersMA.+The+extraperitoneal+space%3A+normal+and+pathologic+anatomy.+In%3A+Meyers+MA%2C+ed.+Dynamic+radiology+of+the+abdomen.+5th+ed.+New+York%2C+NY%3A+Springer-Verlag%2C+2000%3B+333%E2%80%93492.">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div></div></section></div></section></div><div class="core-collateral" role="dialog" aria-modal="true"><div id="core-collateral-info" data-active-pane="false"><header><h2><i class="icon-info" aria-hidden="true"></i>Information &amp; Authors</h2></header><section id="tab-information" role="tabpanel"><h3>Information</h3><section class="core-self-citation"><h4>Published In</h4><div class="core-journal-presentation">



        
        <div class="cover-image flat d-flex justify-content-center flex-column"><div data-is-viewable="" class="cover-image__image"><a href="/toc/radiographics/27/1" title="Go to RadioGraphics " class="d-block"><img src="/cms/10.1148/radiographics.2007.27.issue-1/asset/14a16856-1514-1685-4151-a1685641514a/radiographics.2007.27.issue-1.cover.gif" alt="Go to RadioGraphics " loading="lazy"/></a></div></div>
<div class="core-journal-description"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">27</span></span> • <span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">1</span></span> • <span property="datePublished">Jan 1 2007</span></div><div class="core-pagination"><span class="heading">Pages</span>: <span class="content"><span property="pageStart">129</span> - <span property="pageEnd">143</span></span></div><div class="core-pmid"><span class="heading">PubMed</span>: <a class="content" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17235003/" property="sameAs" target="_blank" title="Link to PubMed">17235003</a></div></div></div></section><section class="core-copyright"><h4>Copyright</h4><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2007.</div></section><section class="core-history"><h4>History</h4><div><b class="core-label">Published online</b>: Jan 1 2007</div></section><section class="core-permissions"><h4>Permissions</h4><div>Request permissions for this article.</div><div><a class="btn" href="https://marketplace.copyright.com/rs-ui-web/mp/search/all/10.1148%2Frg.271065050">Request Permissions</a></div></section><section class="core-article-notes"><h4>Notes</h4><div role="paragraph">The normal anatomy of the perihepatic space is reviewed, intraperitoneal flow dynamics and the spectrum of pathologic conditions occurring in this compartment are described, and the associated CT findings and differential diagnoses are discussed.</div></section></section><section id="tab-contributors" role="tabpanel"><h3>Authors</h3><section class="core-authors"><h4>Affiliations</h4><div id="con1" property="author" typeof="Person"><div class="heading"><span property="givenName">Suk</span> <span property="familyName">Kim</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></div><div class="content"><div class="affiliations